			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: EverQuest 2 NDA Lifted.<a name="67173"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 16 04 2:55 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I did enjoy reading Klapton's post &quot;What a mess, Mc.....&quot;
<br />

<br />

<br />
EQII Review:
<br />

<br />
Over all I think the developers really came through, you can tell they were fans of the game and fine-tuned it accordingly. It’s going to take some adjusting so pretty much what you knew from EQLive is going to be very different in EQII. Communication wise everything is about the same, group chat, guild chat, tells, auctions, etc…
<br />

<br />
Some people had mixed feeling about locked encounters, but I found it kind of ironic considering how people were looking forward to avoiding KSing. Most people warmed up to the Heroic Opportunities and Group Chains, that will take a little bit of adjusting to, perhaps a more clearer explanation will be provided in the tutorial upon release.
<br />

<br />
Prepare to do a lot of double clicking, adjusting to the Con Colors 
<br />
&amp; Targeting (Group Mob, Solo Mob definitions), armor and weapon knowledge, harvesting, space usage (bags, bank, shared bank slots), grouping as well as soloing tactics, learning the interface and interacting with NPC’s.
<br />

<br />
Performance: 
<br />

<br />
I have a 2.8Ghz, 1Ghz RAM, SoundBlaster Live Audigy 2 and an ATI 9600 Pro, everything seem to run really well at the default setting. I made a few adjustments for content and it seem to run pretty good. I don’t expect even the newest cards to be able to play on full settings, but then I don’t have the 6800 Ultra to try it out.
<br />

<br />
Graphics:
<br />

<br />
Wow, that pretty much sums it up. Very impressive, nice detailing, great vistas, lots of little immersive touches adds a lot of flavor.   
<br />

<br />
Character Creation:
<br />

<br />
I didn’t spend a lot of time tweaking my character; however there seems to be a decent amount of variety to choose from to add your own personal distinction. 
<br />

<br />
Tutorial: 
<br />

<br />
Very user friendly, easy to navigate, basic enough for even the most computer challenged person to understand. It could use a little fine-tuning in explaining Heroic Opportunities, Chains and Trade Skills, at least in my opinion. I know I struggled a little to understand them.
<br />

<br />
Quest system:
<br />

<br />
Hailing an NPC will start a select dialog, you chose from the various dialogs to then interact with the NPC. If you decide to take up a quest then you will be provided with a journal. The journal covers the over all explanation of the quest, the quest location, what task you are to do and the amount of items you are to collect or areas/items you most locate. You do not have to actually loot any of the items; they will be tabulated in the journal.
<br />

<br />
At the time there wasn’t a way to abandon or delete a quest this lead to some people having tons of quest littering their journal and created a little confusion on where the NPC was that gave certain quest. Some quest will require a small group or full group, though a lot of them are soloable. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
Combat:
<br />

<br />
I’m sure there is a lot of information and opinions on combat; the basics are that in EQII you now have Heroic Opportunities and Chains. Tactics are a lot different in how you interact with a set group of pulled Mobs, single pull is pretty straight forward, grouped Mob combat will take some adjusting too, the Mobs seem to use a little more tactics and aren’t as easily manipulated as they are in EQLive. 
<br />

<br />
 
<br />
Trade Skills:
<br />

<br />
Very interesting system, its much more involved now and its very interactive. One of the controversies of trade ‘skilling’ was that you could die while crafting. Without going into all the meat and potatoes of it, suffice to say that like in combat there are a series of tactics you have to use with your abilities/spell/trade skill book (much like casting spells or using melee abilities in combat) that have to be selected to keep from receiving damage or degrading your product. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
Balance:
<br />

<br />
Over all people seemed somewhat satisfied if not very satisfied with their characters abilities, granted there were some legitimate arguments about certain classes, so changes were made, adjustments were implemented and there will probably be a little more fine tuning before release. 
<br />

<br />
World Map:
<br />

<br />
All cities have maps. You can hover your mouse over locations on the map to determine where certain places are. Some people didn’t like the round red dot that marked your location because you weren’t able to see what direction you were traveling in, however a quick look at your compass would help you out. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
